"""
mkt-context fill — 2 Kings ch21-22
Covers: 43 missing verses (ch21: 25 missing v1-5,7-18,19-26; ch22: 18 missing v1-7,9-13,15-20)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-2kings-21-22-fill.py

Key decisions:
- Ch21: Manasseh's 55-year reign (697-642 BC) — longest in Judah; eventual repentance per 2 Chr 33
- Ch21 v16: "innocent blood" — ancient tradition identifies this as the martyrdom of Isaiah
- Ch22: The 18th year of Josiah = 622 BC; book found is likely Deuteronomy or a core portion
- Ch22 v14: Huldah the prophetess — one of few named female prophets; her oracle controls the chapter's meaning
- 2 Chr 34 gives a different chronology of Josiah's reforms (beginning in year 12) vs. 2 Kings (year 18)
"""

import json
import pathlib

def load_comm(path):
    p = pathlib.Path(path)
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(path, data):
    pathlib.Path(path).write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=2))

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    # INTENT: Merge new commentary entries without overwriting existing ones — safe to re-run
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

DATA = {
"21": {
"1": "<p>Manasseh&#8217;s regnal formula: twelve years old when he became king, reigning fifty-five years in Jerusalem (697–642 BC). His fifty-five year reign is the longest of any Davidic king — more than twice Hezekiah&#8217;s twenty-nine years. The irony is severe: the son of Judah&#8217;s greatest reforming king reigns longer than any other king and undoes everything his father accomplished. His co-regency with Hezekiah began around 697 BC, explaining the chronological overlap. Ancient Near Eastern parallels for such long reigns (Tiglath-pileser III, Esarhaddon) show that Manasseh ruled as a vassal of Assyria through the reign of Esarhaddon and Ashurbanipal — his longevity partly reflects political accommodation to Assyrian overlordship.</p>",

"2": "<p><em>Wayyaʿaś hārāʿ bᵉʿênê YHWH kᵉtôʿᵉḇôt haGGôyim</em> — he did evil in the sight of YHWH according to the abominations of the nations. The specific reference to the nations YHWH drove out before Israel (<em>ʾăšer hôrîš YHWH mippᵉnê bᵉnê yiśrāʾēl</em>) is the standard judgment phrase for the most severe apostasy in Kings. Manasseh is measured not against previous Israelite kings but against the Canaanite standard — the baseline of paganism that Israel&#8217;s conquest was meant to displace. He reverses not just his father&#8217;s reform but the entire Deuteronomic purpose of the conquest.</p>",

"3": "<p>The reversal of Hezekiah&#8217;s reform is total and explicit: Manasseh rebuilt (<em>wayyiḇen</em>) the high places his father had demolished, erected Baal altars, and made an Asherah as Ahab king of Israel had done. The double comparison — undoing Hezekiah and imitating Ahab — brackets Manasseh between the worst king of Israel and the best king of Judah, placing him emphatically on the wrong side. He also worshipped <em>kol ṣᵉḇāʾ haššāmayim</em> (all the host of heaven) — the astral cult condemned in Deut 4:19 and 17:3. The astronomical/astrological religion was Assyrian in character; Manasseh&#8217;s adoption of it reflects cultural assimilation to his overlords.</p>",

"4": "<p>Manasseh builds altars in the temple itself — <em>bᵉḇêt YHWH</em>. The placement of Baal altars inside the temple of YHWH is the most extreme form of syncretism: not simply worship of other gods alongside YHWH but the introduction of pagan cult objects into the sacred space that represented YHWH&#8217;s exclusive dwelling. The narrator inserts the divine speech about the temple — <em>ʾăšer ʾāmar YHWH bîrûšālayim ʾāśîm ʾet šᵉmî</em> (where YHWH said, in Jerusalem I will put my name) — precisely to heighten the sacrilege: the space of the divine name is profaned.</p>",

"5": "<p>Altars to all the host of heaven in both courts of the temple. The two courts — the inner court of the priests and the outer court of the people — represent the full extent of the sacred precincts. To fill both courts with astral altars is to erase the distinction between sacred and profane throughout the temple complex. The host-of-heaven cult (Babylonian/Assyrian <em>šar šamê</em>) was a sophisticated astral religion practiced throughout the ancient Near East; Manasseh&#8217;s adoption of it integrates the Jerusalem temple into a cosmopolitan imperial religious framework that explicitly displaced YHWH&#8217;s singular claim.</p>",

"7": "<p>The placement of the carved Asherah pole (<em>pesel hāʾăšērāh</em>) inside the temple — in the specific space about which YHWH had spoken to David and Solomon (<em>ʾăšer ʾāmar YHWH ʾel dāwid wᵉʾel šᵉlōmōh bᵉnô</em>) — is the theological nadir. The Asherah, a female fertility deity associated with Baal, is placed in the space where YHWH said his name would dwell forever. The narrator invokes the Davidic covenant promise precisely at this point of maximum violation: the space of the covenant is given to the covenant&#8217;s antithesis. The tradition in 2 Chr 33:11-13 records that Manasseh was later taken captive to Babylon and repented — not mentioned in Kings, which focuses on the national rather than personal dimension.</p>",

"8": "<p>YHWH&#8217;s conditional promise about the land: <em>lōʾ ʾôsîp lᵉhāniʿ regeL yiśrāʾēl min hāʾăḏāmāh</em> — I will no longer cause Israel&#8217;s feet to wander from the land I gave their ancestors — provided they keep all that I commanded them, all the Torah Moses commanded. The condition (<em>raq ʾim yišmᵉrû</em>) connects the land promise to covenant faithfulness. The narrator places this conditional promise here as the standard against which Manasseh&#8217;s failure is measured: the promise was clear; the condition was known; the failure was inexcusable.</p>",

"9": "<p><em>wᵉlōʾ šāmᵉʿû wayyatᵉʿēm mᵉnaššeh laʿăśôt rāʿ mikkol haGGôyim</em> — but they did not listen; Manasseh led them astray to do more evil than all the nations YHWH had destroyed before the Israelites. The comparison exceeds that of v2: not merely acting like the nations but exceeding them in wickedness. The verb <em>tāʿāh</em> (to lead astray, to wander) combines the ideas of deliberate misleading and aimless wandering — Manasseh actively caused Israel to abandon its covenantal path. The moral trajectory of Judah is now downward beyond any previous low point.</p>",

"10": "<p>The prophetic speech formula: <em>waydabbēr YHWH bᵉyaḏ ʿăḇāḏāyw hannᵉḇîʾîm</em> — YHWH spoke by the hand of his servants the prophets. The phrase &#8220;by the hand of&#8221; (<em>bᵉyaḏ</em>) is the standard idiom for prophetic mediation — the prophet is the instrument through which YHWH speaks, not the originator of the word. The shift from historical narrative to prophetic speech marks a theological turning point: history has reached the moment where YHWH must announce its outcome.</p>",

"11": "<p>The indictment: Manasseh has done more evil than the Amorites (<em>haʾĕmōrî</em>) who preceded Israel in the land. The Amorites were the generic designation for pre-Israelite Canaanite populations (cf. Gen 15:16 — &#8220;the iniquity of the Amorites is not yet complete&#8221;). That Manasseh has now surpassed the Amorite standard of wickedness signals that the conditions that justified the original conquest are now reproduced within Israel itself — making Judah subject to the same judgment by the same logic. He has also caused Judah to sin (<em>wayyaḥăṭîʾ ʾet yᵉhûḏāh</em>) with his idols — collective guilt through royal leadership.</p>",

"12": "<p>YHWH&#8217;s announcement: <em>hinnᵉnî mēḇîʾ rāʿāh ʿal yᵉrûšālayim wîhûḏāh</em> — I am about to bring disaster on Jerusalem and Judah. The particle <em>hinnᵉnî</em> (behold me) marks a divine first-person announcement of imminent action. The expression <em>ʾăšer kol šōmᵉʿāyw tiṣṣalnāh šᵉtê ʾoznāyw</em> — both ears of whoever hears it will tingle — is a unique idiom for news of catastrophic scale (cf. 1 Sam 3:11 where the same expression describes the announcement of Eli&#8217;s house&#8217;s end). The disaster will be so severe that the mere report of it will physically affect the listener.</p>",

"13": "<p>The measuring line of Samaria and the plumb line of the house of Ahab will be stretched over Jerusalem: <em>wᵉnāṭîtî ʿal yᵉrûšālayim ʾēt qaw šōmrôn wᵉʾēt miškōlet bêt ʾaḥʾāḇ</em>. The measuring-line image (used in Amos 7:7-9 for the plumb line of judgment) applies to Jerusalem the same standard of destruction used against Samaria and Ahab&#8217;s dynasty — both now destroyed. The image of wiping and turning over a dish — <em>wᵉmāḥîtî ʾet yᵉrûšālayim kaʾăšer yimḥeh ʾet haqqᵉʿāràh</em> — is vivid household imagery: Jerusalem will be wiped clean like a dish and turned upside down, emptied of its contents.</p>",

"14": "<p>YHWH will abandon the remnant of his inheritance and give them into the hand of their enemies. The phrase <em>šᵉʾērît naḥălātî</em> (the remnant of my inheritance) applies the language of covenantal possession to what will be relinquished. Israel was YHWH&#8217;s portion (<em>naḥălāh</em>); abandoning the remnant means withdrawing the covenant protection entirely. The enemies will plunder and despoil them — the passive role that YHWH had formerly taken as warrior-deliverer is now assigned to foreign powers against Israel.</p>",

"15": "<p>The cause stated in full: <em>yaʿan ʾăšer ʿāśû ʾet hārāʿ bᵉʿênāy wayyihyû makkʿîsîm ʾōtî min hayyôm ʾăšer yāṣᵉʾû ʾăḇôtêhem mimmitsrayim</em> — because they have done evil in my sight and have provoked my anger from the day their ancestors came out of Egypt until today. The judgment is not sudden but the culmination of a long history of provocation beginning at the exodus. The Exodus is the starting point of the covenant relationship; rebellion has been continuous since its inception. Manasseh&#8217;s reign is not the beginning of Israel&#8217;s unfaithfulness but its decisive tipping point.</p>",

"16": "<p>Manasseh sheds innocent blood (<em>ḏam nāqî</em>) filling Jerusalem from end to end — <em>mippeh laʾpeh</em> (mouth to mouth = from end to end). The innocent blood motif carries legal and theological weight: innocent blood cries from the ground (Gen 4:10; Deut 19:10-13) and defiles the land, requiring expiation. The tradition that Manasseh executed the prophet Isaiah by having him sawn in half (reflected in Heb 11:37) is ancient and consistent with this notice of filling Jerusalem with innocent blood. The scale — filling the city — suggests systematic persecution of the faithful, not merely individual executions.</p>",

"17": "<p>The standard regnal summary: Manasseh&#8217;s other acts and all he did, and the sin he committed, are recorded in the chronicles of the kings of Judah. The notation of &#8220;the sin he committed&#8221; (<em>waḥaṭṭāʾṯô ʾăšer ḥāṭāʾ</em>) as a separate archival category alongside his other acts treats Manasseh&#8217;s apostasy as defining enough to require specific mention in the official records — not just what he did but specifically his sin. The 2 Chronicles account (33:11-20) fills in the record of his captivity, repentance, and restoration, which the Kings narrator omits in order to maintain the judgment framework.</p>",

"18": "<p>Manasseh&#8217;s burial in the garden of his palace, the garden of Uzza — not in the city of David (the royal necropolis). The departure from royal burial tradition (1 Kgs 2:10; 11:43; etc.) signals either spatial constraint in the royal cemetery or deliberate exclusion. The garden of Uzza appears also in v26 for Amon&#8217;s burial. Burial outside the Davidic necropolis may reflect the theological judgment of the narrator: the king who desecrated the temple is buried outside the ancestral space of the covenant kings.</p>",

"19": "<p>Amon&#8217;s regnal formula: twenty-two years old, reigned two years (642–640 BC). The brevity of his reign contrasts maximally with his father&#8217;s fifty-five years. Amon&#8217;s mother Meshullemeth is from Jotbah — an otherwise unknown location, possibly in Galilee or the Negev. The short reign follows the pattern of corrupt kings whose dynasties YHWH truncates; Amon&#8217;s assassination after two years is the natural consequence of continuing Manasseh&#8217;s apostasy without Manasseh&#8217;s longevity.</p>",

"20": "<p>Amon did evil in YHWH&#8217;s sight as his father Manasseh had done. The evaluation is the most condensed possible — he is entirely identified with his father&#8217;s apostasy. The two-verse evaluation (v20-22) uses three different verbs for his religious failure: he did evil (<em>rāʿ</em>), walked in the path of his father (<em>wayyēllek bᵉḵol hadderek ʾăšer hālaḵ ʾāḇîw</em>), and served the idols his father had served (<em>wayyaʿăḇōḏ ʾet haggillûlîm</em>). <em>Gillûlîm</em> (idols, literally &#8220;dung pellets&#8221;) is one of the most contemptuous terms in the prophetic/Deuteronomic vocabulary for pagan cult objects.</p>",

"21": "<p>Amon walked entirely in his father&#8217;s path and served the same idols. The narrative&#8217;s economy here is deliberate — Amon receives minimal individual characterization, functioning as a structural marker: the apostasy of Manasseh continues uninterrupted into the next generation, confirming that it is not merely personal but dynastic and national. The specific detail <em>wayyishtaḥû lāhem</em> (he bowed down to them) adds the posture of active worship to mere toleration of idols.</p>",

"22": "<p>The fundamental failure: <em>wayyaʿăzōḇ ʾet YHWH ʾelōhê ʾăḇōtāyw wᵉlōʾ hālaḵ bᵉdereḵ YHWH</em> — he abandoned YHWH the God of his ancestors and did not walk in the way of YHWH. The language of abandonment (<em>ʿāzaḇ</em>) and the failure to walk in YHWH&#8217;s way inverts Deuteronomy&#8217;s core command (Deut 5:33; 8:6; 10:12). The reference to &#8220;the God of his ancestors&#8221; (<em>ʾĕlōhê ʾăḇōtāyw</em>) invokes the patriarchal covenant that Amon has abandoned — the ancestral relationship that defined Israel&#8217;s identity is severed by deliberate walking away from YHWH.</p>",

"23": "<p>Amon&#8217;s assassination: his servants (<em>ʿăḇāḏāyw</em>) conspired against him and killed him in his own palace. The assassination of a king by his household officials is the most intimate form of political violence — those closest to royal power become its destroyers. Amon&#8217;s murder in his own house (<em>bêtô</em>) mirrors the vulnerability of dynasties built on apostasy. The co-conspirators&#8217; identity and motive are not given; the brevity reflects the narrator&#8217;s focus on the theological trajectory rather than the political details.</p>",

"24": "<p>The popular response: <em>ʿam hāʾāreṣ</em> (the people of the land) killed all who had conspired against Amon and made his son Josiah king in his place. The &#8220;people of the land&#8221; are the landowning class of Judah — a socially conservative force that had acted similarly after Athaliah&#8217;s usurpation (2 Kgs 11:14-20). Their killing of the conspirators and installation of the legitimate heir shows the persistence of Davidic legitimacy in popular consciousness even after Manasseh&#8217;s apostasy. Josiah, though only eight years old, is the people&#8217;s choice as the continuation of the Davidic line.</p>",

"25": "<p>The regnal summary notice for Amon: his other acts are written in the chronicles of the kings of Judah. The archive reference is even briefer for Amon than for Manasseh — his reign was too short to generate much administrative record. The summary closes the Amon episode with maximum efficiency, pivoting the narrative toward Josiah.</p>",

"26": "<p>Amon&#8217;s burial: in his tomb in the garden of Uzza (the same garden as Manasseh&#8217;s burial, v18). Like his father, Amon is buried outside the Davidic city-of-David necropolis. The dynasty&#8217;s burial outside the royal ancestral ground continues; the geography of burial reflects the theological displacement of both kings from the covenantal norm. His son Josiah becomes king — the transition line that begins the chapter of Judah&#8217;s last great reform before the inevitable end.</p>"
},
"22": {
"1": "<p>Josiah&#8217;s regnal formula: eight years old when he became king, reigning thirty-one years (640–609 BC). The accession at age eight — among the youngest of Judah&#8217;s kings — means his early years were effectively a regency. His thirty-one year reign matches the theological weight given to this period: long enough for a full reform, short enough to be cut off before Jerusalem&#8217;s destruction. His mother Jedidah is from Bozkath (in the Shephelah lowlands), giving his lineage a Judean provincial connection rather than a Jerusalemite court background.</p>",

"2": "<p>The evaluative formula for Josiah is the highest in Kings: <em>wayyaʿaś hayyāšār bᵉʿênê YHWH wayyēlek bᵉkol derek dāwîḏ ʾāḇîw wᵉlōʾ sār yāmîn ûśᵉmōl</em> — he did right in the sight of YHWH and walked in all the way of his father David, turning neither to the right nor to the left. The language &#8220;neither right nor left&#8221; (from Deut 17:20; Josh 1:7) is the standard of perfect covenantal adherence. The comparison to David (not merely to &#8220;right&#8221; kings like Hezekiah) places Josiah at the apex of the Davidic tradition. His reform will be more thorough than any since David.</p>",

"3": "<p>The narrative begins in Josiah&#8217;s eighteenth year (622 BC) — thirteen years after he presumably began exercising independent royal authority. The eighteen-year marker anchors the temple reform to a specific historical moment during Assyria&#8217;s decline (Ashurbanipal died c. 627 BC; Babylon was reasserting independence). Josiah sends Shaphan son of Azaliah, grandson of Meshullam — the secretary (<em>hassōpēr</em>) — to the high priest Hilkiah. Shaphan&#8217;s family becomes central to Josiah&#8217;s reform and to Jeremiah&#8217;s protection (Jer 26:24; 36:10).</p>",

"4": "<p>The temple repair commission: Josiah instructs Shaphan to have Hilkiah total (<em>yattem</em>) the money that has been brought into the house of YHWH — what the doorkeepers have collected from the people. The temple collection mechanism described (doorkeepers receiving from the people) mirrors the restoration of temple finance after Joash&#8217;s earlier repair project (2 Kgs 12:9-16). The revival of proper temple administration under Josiah is the institutional precondition for the discovery of the book — the repair work creates the occasion for the finding.</p>",

"5": "<p>The money is to be given to the supervisors of the work (<em>mᵉpaqᵉḏê haMMelāʾkhāh</em>) who oversee the house of YHWH. They in turn distribute it to the workers repairing the temple. The administrative chain — king → secretary → high priest → work supervisors → laborers — reflects a well-organized royal project managed through the temple hierarchy. The specific mention that funds go to workers in the house of YHWH distinguishes this from secular building projects; temple repair is both practical and theological work.</p>",

"6": "<p>The categories of craftsmen enumerated: carpenters (<em>ḥārāšîm</em>), builders (<em>ḇōnîm</em>), and stonemasons (<em>gōḏᵉrîm</em>), along also to buy timber and quarried stone. The three craft categories cover woodwork, general construction, and stonework — all the major components of building repair. The parallel to Joash&#8217;s repair (2 Kgs 12:11-12) is deliberate; Josiah is portrayed as completing the work of the last great reforming king before him, doing what Joash attempted but more thoroughly.</p>",

"7": "<p>The supervisors are not required to audit their expenditure because they act in faithfulness (<em>ʾĕmûnāh</em>). The commendation of the workers&#8217; integrity — <em>kî ḇĕʾĕmûnāh hēm ʿōśîm</em> (they act in faithfulness) — is unusual in the administrative record of temple projects. The explicit trust placed in the workers contrasts with the temple corruption under earlier regimes. Josiah&#8217;s reform begins from a foundation of trusted personnel — the integrity of the workers makes possible the integrity of the entire project.</p>",

"9": "<p>Shaphan returns to the king and reports: your servants have poured out (<em>yittᵉḵû</em>) the money found in the temple and given it to the supervisors of the work. The report is orderly and brief — administrative competence demonstrated. Shaphan then adds the unexpected second item: the priest Hilkiah has given me a book (<em>sēper</em>). The casual grammatical structure — the second clause added without fanfare — mirrors the historical discovery itself: the book of the law is found as a byproduct of temple repair, not through deliberate search.</p>",

"10": "<p>Shaphan reads the book before the king: <em>wayyiqrāʾ ʾōtô šāp̄ān lipnê hammelek</em>. The oral reading of a document before the king was standard administrative practice — royal decisions were made based on read reports. But this reading has unprecedented consequences: the hearing of the covenant stipulations, long forgotten, confronts the king with the gap between what Israel had promised and what it had done. The book&#8217;s content is not specified until the king&#8217;s reaction (v11, v13) implies it contains judgment oracles for covenant violation.</p>",

"11": "<p>The king&#8217;s response: <em>wayhî kiSHmōaʿ hammelek ʾet diḇrê sēper haTTôrāh wayyiqraʿ ʾet bᵉḡāḏāyw</em> — when the king heard the words of the book of the Torah he tore his garments. Tearing garments is the standard expression of profound grief, mourning, and shock in the Hebrew Bible (Gen 37:34; 2 Sam 1:11; 2 Kgs 18:37). Josiah&#8217;s tearing at the words of the Torah indicates that he recognizes the gap between what YHWH requires and what Judah has done — a gap so vast it constitutes a catastrophe already present, even before judgment falls. The immediate tear also signals genuine spiritual response rather than political calculation.</p>",

"12": "<p>Josiah commands a delegation to inquire of YHWH: Hilkiah the priest, Ahikam son of Shaphan (who later protects Jeremiah from death, Jer 26:24), Achbor son of Micaiah, Shaphan the secretary himself, and Asaiah the king&#8217;s servant. The five-man delegation is senior enough to represent royal authority while including both priestly (Hilkiah) and scribal (Shaphan) expertise. The command to inquire for the king, the people, and all Judah (<em>baʿăḏî ûḇaʿaḏ hāʿām ûḇaʿaḏ kol yᵉhûḏāh</em>) expands the inquiry&#8217;s scope from personal to national — Josiah seeks YHWH&#8217;s word for the entire covenant community.</p>",

"13": "<p>The reason for the inquiry: <em>kî ḡᵉḏôlāh ḥămat YHWH ʾăšer hîʾ niṣṣᵉtāh ḇānû</em> — for great is YHWH&#8217;s wrath that has been kindled against us. Josiah&#8217;s fear is that the book&#8217;s curses for covenant violation are already operative — the wrath is &#8220;kindled&#8221; (<em>niṣṣᵉtāh</em>, perfect aspect) indicating an already-accomplished divine judgment. The phrase <em>ʿal ʾăšer lōʾ šāmᵉʿû ʾăḇōtênû ʿal diḇrê hasēper hazzeh</em> — because our ancestors did not hear the words of this book — places the crisis in historical perspective: generations of ignorance of the Torah have accumulated a debt of judgment that Josiah now perceives for the first time.</p>",

"15": "<p>Huldah&#8217;s oracle opening: <em>kōh ʾāmar YHWH ʾelōhê yiśrāʾēl</em> — thus says YHWH the God of Israel. Huldah speaks as a prophet, not as an interpreter or adviser; she mediates the divine word directly. Her oracle falls into two parts: judgment on Jerusalem (v16-17) and a specific word for Josiah (v18-20). The judgment word comes first and is unconditional — the disaster announced in ch21&#8217;s prophetic speech will not be averted. Huldah&#8217;s prophetic authority confirms that even faithful leadership cannot reverse decades of accumulated covenant violation.</p>",

"16": "<p>The disaster oracle: <em>hinnᵉnî mēḇîʾ rāʿāh ʿal hammāqôm hazzeh wᵉʿal yōšᵉḇāyw</em> — I am about to bring disaster on this place and its inhabitants. The language echoes ch21:12 — the announcement made in Manasseh&#8217;s time is now confirmed through a different prophetic voice at the end of the Josiah reform. The words of the book that the king of Judah has heard have been fulfilled: all the curses written in it will come to pass. The book&#8217;s curse-catalog (Lev 26; Deut 28) is the judicial framework for the disaster; Huldah certifies its application.</p>",

"17": "<p>The reason for the disaster: they have abandoned YHWH (<em>ʿāzᵉḇûnî</em>) and burned incense to other gods, provoking YHWH&#8217;s anger with all their handiwork (<em>bᵉḵōl maʿăśēh yᵉḏêhem</em>). The phrase &#8220;all the work of their hands&#8221; covers every manufactured cult object — idols, altars, pillars — the entire apparatus of Manasseh&#8217;s apostasy. <em>Wayyiḥar ʾappî ḇammāqôm hazzeh wᵉlōʾ tiḵḇeh</em> — my anger is kindled against this place and it will not be quenched. The fire image for divine wrath appears throughout the prophets (Jer 4:4; 17:4; 21:12; Ezek 20:47); here it marks the judgment as irreversible, a burning that no reform can extinguish.</p>",

"18": "<p>The specific word for Josiah: <em>wᵉʾel melek yᵉhûḏāh haššōlēaḥ ʾetkem liḏrōš ʾet YHWH</em> — to the king of Judah who sent you to inquire of YHWH. The distinction between the national oracle (vv16-17) and the royal oracle (vv18-20) is important: the disaster on Jerusalem is certain; Josiah&#8217;s personal destiny is different. The inquiry itself — the act of sending to seek YHWH&#8217;s word — is recognized as a distinguishing act of the king. His responsiveness to the Torah is noted and rewarded with a specific word of grace.</p>",

"19": "<p>The reason for Josiah&#8217;s special word: <em>yaʿan raḵ lᵉḇāḇᵉḵā</em> — because your heart was tender/responsive. The adjective <em>raḵ</em> (soft, tender) applied to the heart describes a capacity to be moved by what YHWH says — the opposite of the hardened/stiffened heart of apostasy. Josiah humbled himself (<em>wattikkānaʿ</em>) before YHWH when he heard the Torah&#8217;s words about disaster, tore his garments, and wept before YHWH. These three acts — humbling, tearing, weeping — constitute the full posture of covenantal repentance. YHWH&#8217;s acknowledgment that he has heard (<em>wᵉgam ʾănōḵî šāmaʿtî</em>) mirrors the king&#8217;s hearing of the Torah: the king heard the word; YHWH heard the king.</p>",

"20": "<p>Huldah&#8217;s promise to Josiah: <em>lāḵēn hinnᵉnî ʾōsipᵉḵā ʾel ʾăḇōteḵā wᵉneʾsaptā ʾel qiḇrōteḵā bᵉšālôm</em> — I will gather you to your ancestors, and you will be buried in peace. The promise of dying in peace before the disaster is a specific covenantal mercy: Josiah will not see the destruction of Jerusalem with his own eyes. The irony of the fulfillment is sharp: Josiah dies in battle at Megiddo (2 Kgs 23:29-30) — not the peaceful death the oracle might suggest. The resolution of this tension: Josiah died before the Babylonian destruction of Jerusalem and the exile, spared the sight of the covenant&#8217;s final catastrophe, which is the content of the peace promised.</p>"
}
}

def main():
    out_path = "data/commentary/mkt-context/2kings.json"
    existing = load_comm(out_path)
    before = sum(len(existing.get(c, {})) for c in DATA)
    merge_comm(existing, DATA)
    after = sum(len(existing.get(c, {})) for c in DATA)
    save_comm(out_path, existing)
    print(f"  wrote {out_path}")
    print(f"2kings mkt-context: added up to {after - before} verses across ch21-22")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()
